SIMPLE: whine
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whine
<hw>Whine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Whined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Whining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>whinen</ets>, AS.
<ets>hw⟦imac⟧nan</ets> to make a whistling, whizzing sound; akin to
Icel. <ets>hv⟦imac⟧na</ets>, Sw. <ets>hvina</ets>, Dan.
<ets>hvine</ets>, and probably to G. <ets>wiehern</ets> to neigh, OHG.
<ets>wih⟦omac⟧n</ets>, <ets>hweij⟦omac⟧n</ets>; perhaps of imitative
origin. Cf. <er>Whinny</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>To utter a
plaintive cry, as some animals; to moan with a childish noise; to
complain, or to tell of sorrow, distress, or the like, in a plaintive,
nasal tone; hence, to complain or to beg in a mean, unmanly way; to moan
basely.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Whining</xex> plovers.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hounds were . . . staying their coming, but with a
<qex>whining</qex> accent, craving liberty.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dost thou come here to <qex>whine</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whine
<hw>Whine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter or express plaintively,
or in a mean, unmanly way; <as>as, to <ex>whine</ex> out an
excuse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Whine
<hw>Whine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A plaintive tone; the nasal, childish
tone of mean complaint; mean or affected complaint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whiner</ent>⟦br⟧
